"CORE_NARRATIVE: Traditional light field depth estimation fatally degenerates into **texture copying** in **non-Lambertian regions** due to its blind reliance on the **photo-consistency assumption**, severely hindering real-world 3D reconstruction. To break this physical bottleneck, we decouple reflection components via **MRI-like angular frequency analysis** and **dual-mask physical modeling**, applying tailored estimation strategies for diffuse, specular, and scattering regions. This **component-aware adaptive depth estimation** completely resolves non-Lambertian depth failures, enabling high-fidelity depth prediction across complex, mixed-material environments.\n\nINTRO_HOOK: Open with a striking visual contrast demonstrating how state-of-the-art light field methods perfectly reconstruct Lambertian textures but catastrophically collapse into **texture copying** on everyday specular and scattering objects. Immediately frame this not as a minor edge case, but as a fundamental physical violation of the **photo-consistency assumption** that renders current 3D vision systems unreliable in real-world, predominantly **non-Lambertian regions**.\n\nGAP_BRIDGE: Highlight that while existing methods attempt to mask out or hallucinate non-Lambertian artifacts, they lack physical interpretability and fail to model the underlying light transport and wavevector deflections. Transition to our method by arguing that true robustness requires physically decoupling reflection components via **dual-mask physical modeling** before applying specialized depth estimators, rather than forcing a single flawed **photo-consistency assumption** across all materials.\n\nMETHOD_JUSTIFY: The **MRI-like angular frequency analysis** and **dual-mask physical modeling** are explicitly designed to parse and quantify diffuse, specular, and scattering weights, replacing blind assumptions with physical BRDF constraints. Consequently, the **component-aware adaptive depth estimation** leverages these exact physical weights to route each pixel to its optimal estimator (e.g., EPI for diffuse, photometric stereo for specular), ensuring the fatal **texture copying** failure is structurally prevented.\n\nEXPERIMENT_VALIDATE: Design ablation studies that intentionally isolate **non-Lambertian regions** to prove that without our component decoupling, depth errors spike due to **texture copying**, whereas our tailored strategies maintain sub-pixel accuracy. Furthermore, include real-world mixed-material evaluations to demonstrate that our material classification and dual-mask weighting directly correlate with the elimination of fatal depth degenerations in downstream 3D reconstruction tasks.\n\nCONCLUSION_ECHO: Reiterate that the fatal flaw of the **photo-consistency assumption** in **non-Lambertian regions** is not an unsolvable anomaly, but a physical misalignment successfully corrected through our **component-aware adaptive depth estimation**. Conclude by emphasizing that by restoring physical fidelity via **dual-mask physical modeling**, this work transitions 3D reconstruction from idealized Lambertian assumptions to robust, real-world applicability."